VGI Retreat Workshop

PheWAS R Package

This Rmd file will walk you through an example single SNP PheWAS. The data we will use today is simulated data, generated to reflect the real pattern of correlation found in the EHR. You have been provided one SNP, rs8050136, which is additively coded. There are three potential covariates included: age, is.male, and bmi. Remember that you can view documentation for the PheWAS package methods and other R functions using ?, e.g. ?phewas. In addition, the vignette contains a walkthrough and is available using vignette(PheWAS-package).

Install PheWAS

We first need to install and load the PheWAS package:

install.packages("devtools")
install.packages(c("dplyr","tidyr","ggplot2","MASS","meta","ggrepel","DT")) #May be necessary due to devtools issues
devtools::install_github("PheWAS/PheWAS")
library(PheWAS)

Load data

There are a number of ways to load data, and we may have a variety of data sources for our analysis. First, we will load our genotype data from our plink raw file. It may be necessary to set or change your working directory (setwd and getwd). Alternatively, you can specify the complete path to the file you wish to load. Note that knitr requires us to use a special setup for the working directory above.

setwd("~/vgi_retreat/")
genotypes=read.table("exome_fto.raw",head=T) %>% select(FID,rs8050136_A)

We only need to keep the id and snp allele count columns. We can take a quick peek at our data to make sure it is coded properly and see our allele frequencies.

table(genotypes$rs8050136_A)
## 
##    0    1    2 
## 3597 4797 1600

Next, we read our ICD9 code data from a csv file. We specify the data types of the columns as R will want to read ICD-9 codes as numeric values.

id.icd9.count=read.csv("id.icd9.count.csv", colClasses=c("integer","character","integer"))

Lastly, we will read our covariates in. These are saved in an RData file, which is a compressed, R specific file format.

load("covariates.RData")

Prepare Data

Using the raw format data from plink means our genotype data will be ready to go. We are not going to transform our covariates either, so that leaves us to set up our phenotypes. The below call will use the default minimum code count of 2. This may take a few minutes to complete. Note that we are restricting some phenotypes that are specific to males or females, eg prostate cancer.

phenotypes=createPhewasTable(id.icd9.count,id.gender = covariates %>% transmute(id=FID, gender=ifelse(is.male,"M","F")))
## Mapping ICD-9 codes to phecodes...
## Aggregating codes...
## Mapping exclusions...
## Joining, by = "exclusion_criteria"
## Coalescing exclusions and min.code.count as applicable...
## Reshaping data...

We can actually export this data to a phenotype file that would work with plink if interested. These can be quite large, so we are restricting to a single phenotype here

plinkPhewasExport(phenotypes %>% select(id, `250.2`),file="plink.pheno")

We can pass in these separate data frames we have now loaded directly into the phewas method, but we may want to investigate our data later, so we will merge it ourselves. Note that we need to specify the names of our id columns using the by parameter.

data=inner_join(inner_join(covariates,genotypes),phenotypes, by=c("FID"="id"))
## Joining, by = "FID"

Run PheWAS

Running the PheWAS on a single SNP will not take very long, but we can speed it up using more cores. We will pass phewas the data frame we have merged already, so we need to tell it the names of the columns that contain the phenotypes, genotypes, and covariates. I get the names from the phenotype data frame and remove FID, which is the first element. Note that you can adjust the number of cores as applicable to your system- be sure to play nicely if you are sharing a server!

results=phewas(phenotypes=names(phenotypes)[-1], genotypes=c("rs8050136_A"), covariates=c("age", "is.male"), data=data, cores=4)
## Starting cluster...
## Cluster created, finding associations...

Head gives the top n rows (6 by default), addPhecodeInfo adds the name of the phewas code to the data frame, and arrange orders the data frame according to p-value. We can report all associations from the PheWAS with p<1e-6 using the code below. Theres also a handy method for creating an easy to use table in your knitted document! One can export the table with write.csv(), enabling it to be read by any spreadsheet software.

phewasDT(results)
write.csv(addPhecodeInfo(results) %>% arrange(p) %>% filter(p<1e-6) %>% select(phecode, description, snp, OR, p, n_total, n_cases, n_controls), file="top-results.csv")

Note that our top results are three phecodes that look very similar. As you may remember, phecodes are hierarchical. We shouldnt be surprised to see the overlap in association here- the cases for each test are largely overlapped.

Plot the Results

Creating a rough visualization is straight forward.

phewasManhattan(results)

Try tweaking the plot using parameters, such as title. You can view other options using ?phenotypePlot, ?phenotypeManhattan, and ?phewasManhattan (they all direct to the same place). Remember that most parameters from phenotypePlot can be used in the higher level plotting functions as well.

my_plot=phewasManhattan(results, title="My example plot", annotate.angle=0)
my_plot

If you wish to plot directly to file, you can use png or pdf:

png("MyPlot.png")
my_plot
dev.off()
## png 
##   2

Note that changing the size and scale of the output plot can affect how it looks. The method ggsave from ggplot2 can be helpful for getting consistent output.

Adjusting for BMI (sometimes)

Lets take a look at the effects of BMI on these associations. The phewas function allows one run sets of associations with an adjustment and one without, in addition to any standard covariates. No need to run the analysis again, but heres how one might do it.

results=phewas(phenotypes=names(phenotypes)[-1], genotypes=c("rs8050136_A"), covariates=c("age", "is.male"), adjustments=list(NA,"bmi"), data=data, cores=4)

Phenotypes predicting phenotypes

What happens if we predict phenotypes with our bmi variable?

results_bmi=phewas(phenotypes=names(phenotypes)[-1], predictors = c("bmi"), covariates=c("age", "is.male"), data=data, cores=4, additive.genotypes = F)
## Starting cluster...
## Cluster created, finding associations...
## Compiling results...
## Cleaning up...

One will often see incredibly strong results in these cases, so dont be surprised! In addition, heres the raw code for creating a browsable data table- easily customized from the above default method phewasDT.

DT::datatable(results_bmi %>% addPhecodeInfo() %>% arrange(p) %>% filter(!is.na(p)) %>% transmute(phecode, description, predictor, OR=round(OR,2), p=signif(p,2), n_total, n_cases, n_controls))

Conclusions

Congratulations, you have successfully run a PheWAS using R (and perhaps knitted your first markdown file)!
